scenario:
The code fragment directly passes the return value of the C library function strerror (type char *) to BSP_DEBUG/printf without declaring a pointer variable. This itself is not a violation of MISRA C:2023 Rule 8.13 because the pointer value originates from a standard library prototype (which returns a non-const char *), and the code does not attempt to modify the pointed-to characters. A violating scenario would be if the code stored the result in a non-const pointer when it could be const, e.g.:

char *msg = strerror(status);
BSP_DEBUG("%s\n", msg);

This should be written as

const char *msg = strerror(status);

so the pointer is const-qualified (or use a library function that returns a const-qualified pointer).
